******
[1] Isle of Man
Date: Mon 27 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Isle of Man Online [edited]
<http://www.iomonline.co.im/ViewArticle2.aspx?SectionID=870&ArticleID=861726>

Food poisoning hits island
------------------------
A serious salmonella outbreak, which has spread across England and Northern
Ireland, has hit the Isle of Man. "There has been a sharp increase in the
number of notifications of cases of food poisoning in the Island," said Dr.
Parameswaran Kishore, public health consultant. "On investigating this, it
has become clear that the cases in the Isle of Man are a part of a much
larger outbreak occurring across England and Northern Ireland."
"The specific organism responsible for the outbreak is Salmonella Newport.
The outbreak seems to have started in north east Lincolnshire and has
affected the West Midlands, Northern Ireland, and the Isle of Man. The
investigation of the likely source is being coordinated from London," Dr.
Kishore added.
More than 100 people have been affected by the outbreak so far, the
majority of cases coming in the 20 to 40 age bracket.
Dr. Kishore said no definite source had been identified, but Salmonella
Newport can be present in a large number of foods. "As far as the Island is
concerned, it is clear that the food product causing the outbreak is likely
to have come from abroad rather than one produced locally," he said.
